  "text": "In the present study Arg significantly reduced the elevated levels of inflammatory cytokines (TNF-α and IL-6) Data are presented as mean ± S.D. for 10 rats, a P ≤ 0.05 compared with normal group using ANOVA followed by Bonferroni as a post-ANOVA test. Data are presented as mean ± S.D. from 10 rats, a P ≤ 0.001, b P ≤ 0.01 compared with the normal group, * P ≤ 0.05 compared with the n-ZnO-intoxicated group, respectively, using ANOVA followed by Bonferroni as a post-ANOVA test. Table 6 Effect of Qur and/or Arg treatment on body weight, kidney weight, and kidney/body weight % in intoxicated rats with a high dose of n-ZnO particles compared with n-ZnO treated group. Moreover, Arg alone or in combination with Qur significantly decreased serum creatinine level as compared with rats intoxicated with a high dose of n-ZnO particles. This was attributed to the fact that Arg has various metabolic and immunologic effects and has been considered to be conditionally essential, particularly under inflammatory and oxidative stress [CITATION_1] . It has protective effects against oxidative stress and inflammation in different pathological conditions [CITATION_2] . It can modulate the inflammatory response by modulating the production of inflammatory mediators, such as C-reactive protein as well as cytokine release from activated immune competent cells which play a crucial role in the progression of the pathology [CITATION_3] . Elevation of CRP level post_n-ZnO administration compared with the normal control group in the current work was in accordance with the work of Kim et al. [CITATION_4] , who clarify that CRP is related to the incidence of many pathological condition as coronary heart disease, hypertension, and inflammation. Both Qur and/or Arg treatments reduced CRP level compared with n-ZnO intoxicated group. This is in agreement with Kleemann et al. [CITATION_5] who clarified that dietary intake of flavonoids such as Qur was associated with lower CRP levels. Moreover, Wu et al. [CITATION_6] found that Arg can modulate inflammatory response by modulating the production of inflammatory mediators, such as C-reactive protein.",
